Coronavirus: stay up to date
Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Barbados. See information on measures introduced in Barbados to limit the spread of the virus. Find out how to return to the UK from Barbados.
See coronavirus travel advice for guidance on international travel.
Sign up for email alerts for Barbados travel advice.
British nationals wishing to leave Barbados should contact their airline or travel company and their insurance provider as soon as they are able, and keep up to date with the latest developments. International travel may become more difficult.
The Government of Barbados has announced that, from Sunday 22 March, all visitors arriving from the United Kingdom, Europe and the United States will be placed in quarantine for 14 days, regardless of if they are showing any symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone arriving with a travel history from China, Iran, and South Korea are also subjected to a 14 day quarantine.
The Barbados Ministry of Health and Wellness has a coronavirus hotline staffed by public health officers 24 hours a day on +1 246 536 4500. The Government has announced that all public gatherings such as sporting and cultural events or any event that attracts crowds will be restricted to 100 persons. Visits by members of the public to all public and private geriatric institutions have been suspended until further notice. See Coronavirus.
Most visits to Barbados are trouble free, but there have been incidents of crime including armed robbery and sexual assault. See Crime
The hurricane season normally runs from June to November. You should monitor local and international weather updates from the US National Hurricane Centre and follow the advice of local authorities, including any evacuation orders. See Natural disasters
UK health authorities have classified Barbados as having a risk of Zika virus transmission. For more information and advice, visit the website of the National Travel Health Network and Centre website.
Although there’s no recent history of terrorism in Barbados, attacks can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
The Overseas Business Risk service offers information and advice for British companies operating overseas on how to manage political, economic, and business security-related risks.
The UK-Barbados reciprocal healthcare agreement was terminated in October 2016. See Coronavirus.
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
